    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.37a.21a"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">21a</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">M</hi>c<hi rend="caps">GILVRY INSURANCE AGENCY
                        <lb/>
                    1413 S.</hi> Higgins Avenue . Missoula, Montana 59801
                        <lb/>
                    Phone 543-8091
                        <lb/>
                    Home 543-5563
                        <lb/>
                    _________________________________________________________________________
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italics">Casualty ∙ Fire ∙ Property ∙ Vehicle ∙ Homeowners</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 14, 1973</dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>% University of Nebraska Press</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebraska   68508</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am enclosing a check that I hope will cover the cost and postage of one of your books. I would be so highly delighted to have your autograph. I have read so man<del>u</del><add>y</add> of your stories again and again.</p>
                
                <p>I would not be particular as to which book,as I have thoro<del>g<unclear/></del><add>ug</add>hly enjoyed everthing that I have read of yours. I have just finished 'The River and I' and had a particular warm spot for that as some of my youthful days were spent along the Missouri at Great Falls, Montana.</p> 
                
                <p>My high school days were spent in Springfield,Missouri and I so vividly remember an evening hearing you lecture and do some of your works there at the <hi rend="caps">S.T.C.</hi> Auditorium. <del>there<unclear/></del> This was sometime in 1926 or '27. Periodically through the years, I re-discover a fond memory of hearing you echo the'Song of Three Friends.' I had a hard-bound book of this down through the times and it was always an inspiration for me when the going was rough.</p> 
                
                <p>Most of my life has spent in Montana except for a hitch in the Navy and the above mentioned so-journ in the Missouri Ozarks. Now at this year of 1973 I find your stories again. 'The Splendid Wayfaring' and 'The River and I' were given to me just lately. I am again reading 'Black Elk Speaks'.</p> 
                
                <p>Not long ago a neighbor told me he had seen you on a night <hi rend="caps">TV</hi> talk show and had enjoyed you immensely. I certainly wish I had seen you again. I shall send this letter to one of your publishers and hope they will forward it on to you.</p> 
                
                <p>Thanks again and again for some happy and fulfilling hours down through the years !!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very truly,</salute>
                
                    <signed>J<unclear/> McGilvry</signed>
                
                    <note>JM</note>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">TAX AND ACCOUNTING SERVICE</hi> 
                </fw>
                
            </div1>
